Karlena Ochoa

Descriptive stats - n per income group Threshold is 2

df%>%
  group_by(income_cat) %>%
  summarise(n = n())
## # A tibble: 3 × 2
##   income_cat        n
##   <fct>         <int>
## 1 Higher Income   763
## 2 Lower Income    331
## 3 <NA>              2

Models with cog stim as predictor

Plot 1 - Mean stim and STEM school performance

#mean stim and stem performance
ggplot(df, aes(x = stim_mean, y = zstemx5, color = income_cat)) +
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  labs(x = "Average Caregiver Cognitive Stimulation",
       y = "STEM School Performance", 
       color = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = 'Dark2') +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 459 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).

Plo1 1a - B & W option

#mean stim and stem performance

ggplot(df, aes(x = stim_mean, y = zstemx5, linetype = income_cat)) +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, color = "black") +
  labs(x = "Average Caregiver Cognitive Stimulation",
       y = "STEM School Performance", 
       linetype = "",
       fill = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Plot 1b - with individual data points

#mean stim and STEM school performance 
ggplot(df, aes(x = stim_mean, y = zstemx5, color = income_cat)) +
  geom_smooth(method=lm,se = FALSE) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Average Caregiver Cognitive Stimulation",
       y = "STEM School Performance", 
       color = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = 'Dark2') +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")
